- !<Text/ccd0c340-1e61-4fca-8cc5-438091a444e2>
  PrefabRemaps:
    []
  Name: Text
  Enabled: true
  RenderOrder: 0
  StretchMode: Stretch
  VerticalAlignment: Top
  HorizontalAlignment: Left
  MeshShadowMode: None
  ShadowColor: {x: 1.000000, y: 1.000000, z: 1.000000, w: 1.000000}
  ShadowDensity: 1.000000
  Text: |
    > This is Alessio from the Developer Experience team for Spectacles. 
    
    > I am also a Unity developer for more than 10 years, it was the main way to build app at Magic Leap
    
    > I have been hesitant to learn new tools, but as part of Snap and using these tools everyday I really understood the potential of it. 
    
    > Just because it is one of the major tools available, does not mean it is the best option. 
    
    > Before we get started, let’s just talk about why a Unity developer should start looking into Lens Studio. Let’s be upfront about this: Unity is a great tool, and its major strength is the multi platform deployment workflow. You build for one, you build for all. 
    
    > On the other hand is quite resource intensive software. 

